      children: "Born in 1935 in Mpumalanga, Ndebele artist Esther Mahlangu learned her craft as a child watching and imitating her mother and grandmother; among the Ndebele, most art, including Mahlangu’s specialty of mural painting, is created by women. With a keen eye for composition and color theory, Mahlangu’s work demonstrates the deep history and complex abstraction of Ndebele art. Though the craftswomen who made the Ndebele objects Lydia collected can never be identified, they would have been among Mahlangu’s peers."
    }), "\n", _jsx(_components.p, {
      children: "Over the course of her life, apartheid was instituted and the Ndebele people dispossessed of their land and dispersed. The commitment to distinctively Ndebele styles and crafts by Mahlangu and others cultivated a shared cultural identity that could not be suppressed. Most prominent among these is the vibrant mural art with which many Ndebele women have decorated their homes. Characterized by repeating geometric shapes, bold lines, and bright colors of red, green, blue, yellow, and pink interspersed with black and white, the homes themselves become works of art. The chevron and diamond patterns, the competing graphic elements, had the color choice all spoke to certain rites of passage. Mahlangu speaks to the significance of this work within the community: “When you get married, you paint your first house. It’s very important to have straight lines and not zigzag lines because your family members will come and look. If your lines are perfectly straight, then you are a very good wife and can look after your family.”"
    }), "\n", _jsx(_components.p, {
      children: "Mahlangu achieved international recognition in 1991, when BMW commissioned Mahlangu to paint one of their art cars. The art car project was initiated in 1975 in which BMW invited  renowned artists across the world to use one of their vehicles as their canvas. Andy Warhol, Ry Lichtenstein, and Robert Rauschenberg were among the artists who had already created their own art cars by the time Mahlangu embarked on her own. Painted in Johannesburg over the course of a week, Mahlangu’s art car “[marries] tradition to the essence of BMW,” in her own words. In all her work, Mahlangu paints directly from the imagination, forgoing the use of rulers or other aids to create her lines."
