      children: "As one of the most prominent South African artists today, Mahlangu demonstrates the resilience and potency of Indigenous art, marrying a commitment to traditional forms with a willingness to boldly experiment and adapt to an increasingly globalized world. Often seen wearing traditional Ndebele beadwork and dress, Mahlangu has championed the perseverance of local craft and culture, even as her profile as an artist has grown. To this end, Mahlangu founded an art school that educates youths in the artistic traditions of the Ndebele. For Mahlangu, this, ultimately, is her purpose: “I love to paint and have been doing it my whole life. I will paint anything, as long as there’s a benefit where my culture can be preserved, where somebody growing up can value and never forget their Ndebele roots.”"
